<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25188h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25188h">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25188h"> 188(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font face="wake">C</font> denies mother language</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The <mark>reading of Latin and Greek</mark> does, no doubt, give us &ldquo;intercourse with other minds,&rdquo; but so does the greater literature which exists in modern languages; and we are not now living in the age when Greek was a new study, or when Latin was the common means of communication between scholars ignorant of continental languages. Many of the prejudices and deficiencies of our governing classes are due to their want of scientific knowledge, and to the inordinate importance attached to classical training, and to physical exercise. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 354</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Written sideways on left.  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c14128g" href="c14all.htm#c14128g">VI.C.14:128(g)</a></mm></dd> </dd></dl>
